         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr1982">
            <p>[? lmperator Caesar, son of divus Iulius, designated consul] for the second and [the third] time, (one) of the Tresviri Reipublicae Constituendae, 
               to the Magistrates, Council and People of the Plarasans and Aphrodisians, greetings.</p>
            <p>If you are well it would be good; I too am in good health, together with the army. Solon, son of Demetrios, your ambassador, 
               who has taken the greatest care over the business of your city, has not only been satisfied by the administrative arrangements that have been made 
               but has also urged us to send you from the public records these copies of the edict, the senatus consultum, the treaty and the law that relate to you. 
               For this I praised him, approved him the more, held him as one of my acquaintances and gave him the appropriate privileges, thinking him deserving of honour from us; 
               and I congratulate you on the possession of such a citizen. The copies of the privileges that relate to you are these that are subjoined; 
               I wish you to register them among your public records.</p>
         </div>
